<p id=3D"element-999">There are three characteristics of a binomial experim=
ent.
</p><ol id=3D"element-591"><li>There are a fixed number of trials. Think of=
 trials as repetitions of an experiment. The letter <em data-effect=3D"ital=
ics">n</em> denotes the number of trials.</li>
<li>There are only two possible outcomes, called "success" and "failure," f=
or each trial. The letter <em data-effect=3D"italics">p</em> denotes the pr=
obability of a success on one trial, and <em data-effect=3D"italics">q</em>=
 denotes the probability of a failure on one trial. <em data-effect=3D"ital=
ics">p</em> + <em data-effect=3D"italics">q</em> =3D 1.</li>
<li>The <em data-effect=3D"italics">n</em> trials are independent and are r=
epeated using identical conditions. Because the <em data-effect=3D"italics"=
>n</em> trials are independent, the outcome of one trial does not help in p=
redicting the outcome of another trial. Another way of saying this is that =
for each individual trial, the probability, <em data-effect=3D"italics">p</=
em>, of a success and probability, <em data-effect=3D"italics">q</em>, of a=
 failure remain the same. For example, randomly guessing at a true-false st=
atistics question has only two outcomes. If a success is guessing correctly=
, then a failure is guessing incorrectly. Suppose Joe always guesses correc=
tly on any statistics true-false question with probability <em data-effect=
=3D"italics">p</em> =3D 0.6. Then, <em data-effect=3D"italics">q</em> =3D 0=
.4. This means that for every true-false statistics question Joe answers, h=
is probability of success (<em data-effect=3D"italics">p</em> =3D 0.6) and =
his probability of failure (<em data-effect=3D"italics">q</em> =3D 0.4) rem=
ain the same.</li>
</ol><p id=3D"element-229">The outcomes of a binomial experiment fit a <spa=
n data-type=3D"term" id=3D"term-00001" group-by=3D"b">binomial probability =
distribution</span>. The random variable <em data-effect=3D"italics">X</em>=
 =3D the number of successes obtained in the <em data-effect=3D"italics">n<=
/em> independent trials.</p><p id=3D"element-108">The mean, <em data-effect=
=3D"italics">=CE=BC</em>, and variance, <em data-effect=3D"italics">=CF=83<=
/em><sup>2</sup>, for the binomial probability distribution are <em data-ef=
fect=3D"italics">=CE=BC</em> =3D <em data-effect=3D"italics">np</em> and <e=
m data-effect=3D"italics">=CF=83</em><sup>2</sup> =3D <em data-effect=3D"it=
alics">npq</em>. The standard deviation, <em data-effect=3D"italics">=CF=83=
</em>, is then <em data-effect=3D"italics">=CF=83</em> =3D <span class=3D"o=
