<section data-depth=3D"1" id=3D"element-501"><h2 data-type=3D"title">Notati=
on for the Binomial: <em data-effect=3D"italics">B</em> =3D Binomial Probab=
ility Distribution Function</h2><p id=3D"element-715"><em data-effect=3D"it=
alics">X</em> ~ <em data-effect=3D"italics">B</em>(<em data-effect=3D"itali=
cs">n</em>, <em data-effect=3D"italics">p</em>)</p>
<p id=3D"element-276">Read this as "<em data-effect=3D"italics">X</em> is a=
 random variable with a binomial distribution." The parameters are <em data=
-effect=3D"italics">n</em> and <em data-effect=3D"italics">p</em>; <em data=
-effect=3D"italics">n</em> =3D number of trials, <em data-effect=3D"italics=
">p</em> =3D probability of a success on each trial.</p>
</section><div data-type=3D"example" id=3D"example5" class=3D"ui-has-child-=
title"><header><h2 class=3D"os-title">
  <span class=3D"os-title-label">Example </span>
  <span class=3D"os-number">4.13</span>
  <span class=3D"os-divider"> </span>
</h2></header><section>
<div class=3D"body"><p id=3D"fs-idp328960">It has been stated that about 41=
% of adult workers have a high school diploma but do not pursue any further=
 education. If 20 adult workers are randomly selected, find the probability=
 that at most 12 of them have a high school diploma but do not pursue any f=
urther education. How many adult workers do you expect to have a high schoo=
l diploma but do not pursue any further education?</p>

<p id=3D"element-992">Let <em data-effect=3D"italics">X</em> =3D the number=
 of workers who have a high school diploma but do not pursue any further ed=
ucation.</p>

<p id=3D"element-570"><em data-effect=3D"italics">X</em> takes on the value=
s 0, 1, 2, ..., 20 where <em data-effect=3D"italics">n</em> =3D 20, <em dat=
a-effect=3D"italics">p</em> =3D 0.41, and <em data-effect=3D"italics">q</em=
> =3D 1 =E2=80=93 0.41 =3D 0.59. <em data-effect=3D"italics">X</em> ~ <em d=
ata-effect=3D"italics">B</em>(20, 0.41)</p><p id=3D"fs-idm48754320">Find <e=
m data-effect=3D"italics">P</em>(<em data-effect=3D"italics">x</em> =E2=89=
=A4 12). <em data-effect=3D"italics">P</em>(<em data-effect=3D"italics">x</=
em> =E2=89=A4 12) =3D 0.9738. (calculator or computer)</p>


<div data-type=3D"note" data-has-label=3D"true" id=3D"fs-idm73072400" class=
=3D"statistics calculator ui-has-child-title" data-label=3D""><header><h2 c=
lass=3D"os-title" data-type=3D"title">
  <span class=3D"os-title-label">Using the TI-83, 83+, 84, 84+ Calculator</=
span>
</h2></header><section>
<div class=3D"os-note-body">
<p id=3D"element-224">Go into 2<sup>nd</sup> DISTR. The syntax for the inst=
ructions are as follows:</p>

<p id=3D"element-853"><strong>To calculate (<em data-effect=3D"italics">x</=
em> =3D value): binompdf(<em data-effect=3D"italics">n</em>, <em data-effec=
t=3D"italics">p</em>, number)</strong>
if "number" is left out, the result is the binomial probability table.
<span data-type=3D"newline"><br></span><strong>To calculate <em data-effect=
=3D"italics">P</em>(<em data-effect=3D"italics">x</em> =E2=89=A4 value): bi=
nomcdf(<em data-effect=3D"italics">n</em>, <em data-effect=3D"italics">p</e=
m>, number)</strong> if "number" is left out, the result is the cumulative =
binomial probability table.
<span data-type=3D"newline"><br></span><strong>For this problem: After you =
are in <code data-type=3D"code">2<sup>nd</sup> DISTR</code>, arrow down to =
<code data-type=3D"code">binomcdf</code>. Press <code data-type=3D"code">EN=
TER</code>. Enter 20,0.41,12). The result is <em data-effect=3D"italics">P<=
/em>(<em data-effect=3D"italics">x</em> =E2=89=A4 12) =3D 0.9738.</strong><=
/p>
</div></section></div><div data-type=3D"note" data-has-label=3D"true" id=3D=
"id5442988" data-label=3D"" class=3D"ui-has-child-title"><header><h2 class=
=3D"os-title" data-type=3D"title">
  <span class=3D"os-title-label" data-type=3D"">NOTE</span>
</h2></header><section>
<div class=3D"os-note-body">
<p id=3D"fs-idm93661872">If you want to find <em data-effect=3D"italics">P<=
/em>(<em data-effect=3D"italics">x</em> =3D 12), use the pdf (binompdf). If=
 you want to find <em data-effect=3D"italics">P</em>(<em data-effect=3D"ita=
lics">x</em> &gt; 12), use 1 - binomcdf(20,0.41,12).</p></div></section></d=
iv>

<p id=3D"element-442">The probability that at most 12 workers have a high s=
chool diploma but do not pursue any further education is 0.9738.</p>

<p id=3D"element-586">The graph of <em data-effect=3D"italics">X</em> ~ <em=
